"""
MKT Original Commentary — Joshua chapters 18–20
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-joshua-18-20.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/joshua.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/joshua.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch18–19 are largely boundary/city-list chapters; entries focus on technical
  allotment vocabulary (gôrāl, nāḥălāh, ḥēleq, ḥālaq, gəbûl) rather than
  repeating geographic lists
- Simeon-within-Judah (19:1–9) is treated as deliberate fulfillment of Gen 49:7
- Dan migration (19:47) gets fuller treatment as a narrative anomaly
- Ch20 gets fuller treatment: ʿārêy miqlaṭ legal vocabulary is the philological
  center of the book's climax
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p><em>wayyiqqāhălû kol-ʿăḏat bənê-yiśrāʾēl šilōh</em> — 'the whole assembly of Israel gathered at Shiloh.' The transfer of the cult center from Gilgal (where the Jordan-crossing monuments stood) to Shiloh marks a new phase: the tent of meeting (<em>ʾōhel môʿēd</em> H168) is erected in permanent territory. <em>nikkəbāšāh hāʾāreṣ</em> (H3533) — 'the land was subdued/conquered'; <em>kābaš</em> carries the sense of trampling down, bringing under foot — not just military defeat but enforced submission (cf. Gen 1:28 where Adam is commanded to <em>kibšūhā</em>, subdue the earth). The use here closes the conquest narrative: Canaan is under Israel's foot at last.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>wayyiwwāṯərû bənê-yiśrāʾēl šebaʿ šəḇāṭîm ʾăšer lōʾ-ḥāleqû ʾet-naḥălāṯām</em> — 'seven tribes of Israel remained who had not divided their inheritance.' <em>yāṯar</em> (H3498) means to remain over, be left as a surplus — a residual. The verb <em>ḥālaQ</em> (H2505, divide/apportion) is the dominant verb of the allotment chapters. The <em>nāḥălāh</em> (H5159, inheritance) they have not divided is legally theirs — the delay is procrastination, not dispossession.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Joshua's rebuke: <em>ʿad-mātay ʾattem mitrappîm lāḇōʾ lārešet ʾet-hāʾāreṣ</em> — 'until when are you slack/negligent about going in to possess the land?' <em>rāpāh</em> (H7503) means to let droop, to become slack — related to the idiom 'let your hands fall' (cf. Jer 6:24). Joshua uses the same verb as Moses's critics used against him (Exod 5:8,17 — 'you are idle, idle!'). The irony: Israel was enslaved for reluctance to work; now they are free and reluctant to claim their freedom's full fruit. The land is a gift they must actively receive.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Joshua directs each tribe to appoint three men to survey the remaining land and write its description (<em>kāṯaḇ</em> H3789) in a book (<em>sēfer</em> H5612). The written survey is a legal document — transforming geographic description into title deed. The three-per-tribe delegation (21 men for 7 tribes) ensures proportional tribal representation in the assessment process.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The land is to be divided (<em>ḥālaQ</em>) into seven portions, with Judah retaining the south and Joseph the north. The prior allotments of the two dominant tribes serve as fixed boundaries within which the remaining seven must be assigned. The spatial constraint drives the need for careful measurement and proportional assignment.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>wəʾānōkî ʾašlîk lākem gôrāl pōh lipnê YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</em> — 'I myself will cast the lot for you here before YHWH our God.' <em>gôrāl</em> (H1486) is the lot — a stone, stick, or pebble used for decision-making. The mechanism transfers human preference entirely to divine determination: <em>lōʾ-ḥālaQ libnê yiśrāʾēl</em> would mean human parceling; the lot means YHWH parcels. The phrase <em>lipnê YHWH</em> (before YHWH) at the tent of meeting is the critical locator: this is a covenant ceremony, not a land survey.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levites have no portion (<em>ḥēleq</em> H2506) among the tribes 'because the priesthood of YHWH is their inheritance (<em>nāḥălātām</em>).' The Levitical exclusion from land is the deepest expression of priestly theology: God himself, mediated through sacrificial service, is their possession. <em>ḥēleq</em> and <em>nāḥălāh</em> are near synonyms here, both meaning share/allotment — the point is that Levi's share is non-territorial.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The men commissioned to survey the land go out and walk through it (<em>hālak</em> H1980), writing descriptions (<em>kāṯaḇ</em>) by cities into seven sections (<em>ḥālaqîm</em>). The verb <em>šūṭ</em> (to rove, range across) is not used here; rather <em>hālak</em>, to walk — a deliberate, methodical traversal. The written record anticipates the modern cadastral survey: a formal inventory of territory enabling lawful distribution.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The men traverse the land and describe it in a document with seven divisions, then return to Joshua at Shiloh. The practical geography — towns, boundaries, watersheds — is recorded to enable the lot to be applied to real territory. Without accurate description, the lot's result would be unimplementable. The combination of human survey and divine lot models the integration of careful human work and divine sovereignty.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>wayyapîl yəhôšuaʿ gôrāl lahem bəšilōh lipnê YHWH</em> — 'Joshua cast the lot for them at Shiloh before YHWH.' The lot is cast (<em>nāpal</em> H5307, lit. 'to fall') — the lots 'fall' rather than are 'chosen,' emphasizing that the outcome descends rather than rises. The sanctuary location (lipnê YHWH) converts the lot into a divine verdict. Prov 16:33: 'The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from YHWH.'</p>",
    "11": "<p>Benjamin's lot 'came up' (<em>wayyaʿal gôrāl</em> H5927) — the lot fell between the territory of Judah and the territory of Joseph. The positional description — geographically sandwiched — accurately describes Benjamin's narrow north-south strip. The language 'came up' for the lot suggests the lot was drawn from a container (shaken in a fold of cloth and drawn out).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Benjamin's northern boundary is described from the Jordan westward: <em>wayyaʿal gəḇûlām</em> (the boundary 'goes up,' H1366 H5927) — geographic language treats territory as a three-dimensional surface, with 'going up' meaning moving toward higher elevation or toward the watershed. <em>gəḇûl</em> (H1366, boundary/border) is the key term of these chapters — the line that defines the inherited portion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The boundary descends (<em>yāraḏ</em> H3381) toward Luz (Bethel) and passes toward Ataroth-addar. The alternating 'going up' and 'going down' language tracks the actual topography of the central hill country. Bethel — where Jacob saw the ladder (Gen 28:19) — is on Benjamin's border with Ephraim, and its history of divine encounter gives this boundary geographic and theological weight.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The western boundary turns southward from Kiriath-baal (= Kiriath-jearim, where the ark will later rest, 1 Sam 7:2). The identification of a city by two names — its pre-Israelite name and its Israelite name — is a feature of these chapters, preserving geographic memory across the conquest transition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The southern boundary of Benjamin runs from the edge of Kiriath-jearim westward to the spring of the Waters of Nephtoah (likely Lifta north of Jerusalem). The precise boundary description — springs, valleys, and identifiable landmarks — reflects survey accuracy preserved across centuries of transmission.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The boundary goes down to the foot of the hill facing the Valley of Ben Hinnom, north of the Valley of Rephaim. The Valley of Ben Hinnom (<em>gêʾ ben-hinnōm</em>) will become <em>Gehinnom</em> in later Jewish usage — the dump where refuse burned — and eventually lend its name to the NT concept of hell. Here it is simply a topographic marker on Benjamin's southern border.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The boundary curves from En-shemesh (Spring of the Sun) to En-rogel (Fuller's Spring) — two named springs that served as permanent geographic anchors. Spring names encode function or history; <em>ʿên</em> (H5869/H5878, spring) is the most reliable landmark in an arid landscape, unchanging across centuries.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The boundary continues over the slope opposite the Arabah, then descends to the Arabah. The Arabah (<em>hāʿărāḇāh</em> H6160) is the Jordan Rift Valley — the deepest geographic feature of the region. This corner of Benjamin's territory touches the eastern lowlands, giving the tribe access to multiple ecological zones.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The boundary passes to the north shore of the Salt Sea (<em>yām hammeleḥ</em> H3220 H4417) at the mouth of the Jordan. The Salt Sea (Dead Sea) terminates Benjamin's southeastern corner. <em>meleḥ</em> (salt) describes its chemical character; the same term appears in Ezek 47:8-11 where the Dead Sea is healed but its salt-marshes preserved.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Jordan forms the eastern boundary. The four-sided description is complete: north = ridge above Beth-aven, west = Kiriath-jearim ridge, south = Ben Hinnom / Jordan mouth, east = the Jordan. The territorial precision serves both legal and theological functions — the lot's result is recorded as binding covenant deed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The cities of the tribe of Benjamin are now listed by name. The distinction between <em>gəḇûl</em> (boundary, the linear border) and <em>ʿārîm</em> (cities, the discrete settlements within the territory) marks the transition from boundary description to town inventory — two complementary ways of defining inheritance.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Beth-arabah, Zemaraim, Bethel — the city list begins with places whose names echo broader biblical narratives. Bethel (house of God, H1008) appears both as a boundary marker (vv13) and as a city in the list, reflecting its central importance as a cult site at the tribal border.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Avvim, Parah, Ophrah — cities in the central hill country. Ophrah will later be associated with Gideon (Judg 6:11), demonstrating how these town-list chapters of Joshua provide the geographic foundation for the narratives of Judges. The inheritance that seems merely administrative carries the seeds of the subsequent history.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Chephir-ammoni and Ophni — two more Benjaminite towns. The town list format (<em>ʿārîm</em> with no narrative) is legal, not literary; it functions as title record. The names' preservation across centuries of transmission — even where origins are obscure — reflects the scribal care given to covenant-land records.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Gibeon, Ramah, Beeroth — notable cities. Gibeon (H1391) is where the Gibeonites made their peace with Israel (Josh 9) and where YHWH gives Solomon wisdom (1 Kgs 3:4-5). Ramah (H7414, height) is the birth and burial city of Samuel (1 Sam 1:19; 25:1). Benjamin's town list is simultaneously a legal catalog and a narrative forecast.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Mizpeh, Chephirah, Mozah — Mizpeh (H4709, watchtower/lookout) becomes one of the major tribal gathering places in Judges and Samuel (Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 7:5-12; 10:17). The naming of a watchtower-city points to the defensive topography that characterized Benjamin's territory on the edge of the central ridge.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Rekem, Irpeel, Taralah — the list continues. These cities in Benjamin's territory fill out the picture of a densely settled, strategically located tribe — sitting athwart the main routes between north and south, between the Mediterranean coast and the Jordan Valley.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Zelah, Haeleph, Jebus (that is Jerusalem), Gibeah, and Kiriath — fourteen cities in total. The identification of <em>Yəḇûs</em> (H2982) as Jerusalem (<em>Yərûšālāyim</em>) is significant: Jerusalem is listed as a Benjaminite city, though it remained Jebusite until David's capture (2 Sam 5:6-9). Its inclusion here as an uncaptured city within Benjamin's allotment sets up the canonical anticipation of its eventual conquest and theological centrality.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The second lot (<em>gôrāl šēnî</em>) comes out for Simeon. The ordinal 'second' implies the lots were drawn in sequence, each new lot determining who comes next. Simeon's lot falls <em>bəṯôk naḥălat bənê-yəhûḏāh</em> — 'within the inheritance of the children of Judah.' The preposition <em>bəṯôk</em> (H8432, in the midst of, inside) signals immediately that this allotment is a sub-grant within a prior one — anomalous from the start.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Simeon's cities begin with Beersheba (<em>bəʾēr šebaʿ</em> H884 — Well of Seven or Well of the Oath), the southernmost city of Israel in the formulaic 'from Dan to Beersheba' (Judg 20:1). The patriarchal associations of Beersheba are dense: Abraham's covenant with Abimelech (Gen 21:31), Isaac's altar (Gen 26:23-25), Jacob's departure for Egypt (Gen 46:1). Simeon inherits the southernmost sacred geography.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Hazar-shual (H2705, Fox-enclosure), Balah, and Azem — the city list for Simeon continues with mostly Negeb towns. The place names often encode ecological reality: <em>ḥāṣēr</em> (H2691, enclosure/settlement) appears in many compound names, describing the settled villages of the Negeb where semi-nomadic clans established permanent sites.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Eltolad, Bethul, Hormah — Hormah (H2767, H2763 root: <em>ḥāram</em>, devoted to destruction) marks a site that Israel vowed to destroy (Num 21:3). The name preserves the memory of a <em>ḥērem</em> (sacred destruction) vow. When Simeon inherits this city, the vow has already been fulfilled — the name now is a memorial of obedience rather than an ongoing commitment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ziklag, Beth-marcaboth, Hazar-susah — Ziklag (H6860) will later be given to David by the Philistine king Achish (1 Sam 27:6) — at that point a city not yet fully under Israelite control. Its inclusion in Simeon's list reflects the theoretical allotment; actual possession would be established later.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Beth-lebaoth and Sharuhen — thirteen cities with their villages (<em>ḥăṣērêhem</em> H2691). The summary formula 'cities and their villages' distinguishes between urban centers and their dependent rural settlements — the ancient equivalent of a city and its suburbs or satellite hamlets.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ain, Rimmon, Ether, Ashan — four more cities. Ain (H5871, spring) and Rimmon (H7417, pomegranate) are sometimes treated as a compound Ain-rimmon (cf. Neh 11:29). The fruit-bearing name Rimmon points to the agricultural richness of the Negeb's settlements when wells were maintained and terraces built.</p>",
    "8": "<p>All the villages around these cities to Baalath-beer (Ramah of the Negeb) — the summary includes unnamed villages around the named cities. <em>ḥăṣērîm</em> (villages, H2691) are the agricultural satellites; <em>ḥāṣēr</em> originally described an unwalledenclosure around which temporary structures clustered. Simeon's inheritance is defined as much by this dispersed rural network as by its named cities.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The explanation of Simeon-within-Judah: <em>kî-hāyāh ḥēleq bənê-yəhûḏāh rāḇ mēhem</em> — 'because the share of Judah was too great for them' (lit. too much from them). <em>ḥēleq</em> (H2506, portion/share) is here used of the land itself. The surplus of Judah is redistributed to the landless Simeonites — an economic solution that simultaneously fulfills Jacob's curse on Simeon (Gen 49:7: 'I will scatter them in Israel'). The lot mechanism has achieved what prophecy announced.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The third lot comes up for Zebulun. <em>wayyaʿal gôrāl šəlîšî</em> — 'the third lot came up.' The sequence of lot-drawing continues; each lot determines the next tribe to be placed. Zebulun's territory is in the lower Galilee — Gen 49:13 promised that 'Zebulun will live by the seashore' and 'his haven will be Sidon.' The geographic fulfillment of the patriarchal blessing is a subtext of these allotment chapters.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Zebulun's boundary: <em>wayyaʿal gəḇûlām</em> goes up toward the sea, toward Maralah, touching Dabbesheth. The boundary description uses the same 'going up/down' topographic vocabulary as Benjamin's (ch18), tracking the actual relief of the Galilee hill country. Zebulun's territory straddles the Jezreel Valley and lower Galilee.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The boundary turns eastward from Sarid toward Beth-shemesh. Zebulun's eastern boundary runs toward the Jordan Valley — the tribe sits between the Mediterranean coastal plain and the Sea of Galilee, controlling the important trade routes through the Jezreel Valley (the Via Maris corridor).</p>",
    "13": "<p>From there it passes eastward to Gath-hepher (H1662) and Eth-kazin, and continues to Rimmon, curving to Neah. Gath-hepher is the hometown of the prophet Jonah (2 Kgs 14:25) — its inclusion in the tribal list demonstrates how the inheritance chapters contain the geographic seeds of later prophetic narratives.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The boundary turns northward to Hannathon and ends at the Valley of Iphtah-el. The circuit of Zebulun's territory is complete: a compact tribal region in the lower Galilee, well-watered and agriculturally rich — the same region where Jesus will conduct the majority of his Galilean ministry.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Kattath, Nahalal, Shimron, Idalah, Bethlehem — twelve cities (a different Bethlehem from Judah's, in Zebulun's territory). The recurrence of the name Bethlehem (H1035, house of bread) in multiple tribal territories reflects how common names derived from agricultural productivity (<em>leḥem</em>, bread) were reused across regions.</p>",
    "16": "<p>This is the inheritance (<em>naḥălāh</em>) of Zebulun with its cities and villages. The closing formula for each tribe's allotment standardizes the record: inheritance (covenant term), cities (urban centers), villages (rural network). The formula's consistency implies a common source document — likely a royal cadastral record.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The fourth lot comes out for Issachar. Gen 49:14-15 described Issachar as 'a rawboned donkey crouching between its saddlebags' — a tribe comfortable with agricultural labor and content with its territory. The Jezreel Valley, which Issachar inherits, is the most fertile land in Canaan.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Issachar's cities: Jezreel (<em>yizrəʿēʾl</em> H3157, 'God sows/plants') — the valley itself takes its name from this city. Chesulloth, Shunem — Shunem (H7766) will be the home of the great woman who hosts Elisha (2 Kgs 4:8), demonstrating again how the allotment lists embed the geographic home of later narratives.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hapharaim, Shion, Anaharath — further Issacharite cities in the Jezreel Valley corridor. The valley these cities occupy connects the Mediterranean coast to the Jordan Valley, making Issachar's territory a major crossroads of ancient trade and military movement.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Rabbith, Kishion, Abez — Kishion (H7191) is in the territory that becomes the battle site of Deborah and Barak (Judg 4-5, the Kishon River area). The geographic precision of the allotment lists creates the stage on which subsequent narrative drama unfolds.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Remeth, En-gannim, En-haddah, Beth-pazzez — four cities whose names encode landscape features: <em>ʿêyn</em> (spring), <em>gannîm</em> (gardens), <em>ḥaddāh</em> (sharp/keen, possibly describing a distinctive spring). The spring-names are the most ancient layer of geographic memory, preserved because water sources were permanent landmarks.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The territory touches Tabor, Shahazumah, and Beth-shemesh — sixteen cities in total for Issachar. Mount Tabor (<em>taḇôr</em> H8396) is the prominent isolated peak at the northeastern corner of the Jezreel Valley — a major geographic landmark that will serve as the assembly point for Deborah's coalition (Judg 4:6). Its inclusion as a boundary marker acknowledges its unmistakable visual dominance.</p>",
    "23": "<p>This is the inheritance of Issachar — closing formula. Issachar's territory in the Jezreel Valley gives it the most agriculturally productive land in Canaan, fulfilling Jacob's portrait of a tribe content with its fertile portion (Gen 49:15).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The fifth lot comes out for Asher. Gen 49:20: 'Asher's food will be rich; he will provide delicacies fit for a king.' Asher's coastal territory along the Phoenician border (Carmel to Sidon) gave it access to seafaring trade and the fertile Acco plain. The lot confirms what the patriarchal blessing anticipated.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Asher's cities: Helkath, Hali, Beten, Achshaph — the northern coastal plain. Achshaph (H407) appears in Joshua 11:1 among the northern coalition against Israel; its inclusion in Asher's allotment confirms the conquest. The transformation from enemy city to inheritance city marks the completion of each locality's history.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Alammelech, Amad, Mishal — and it reaches Carmel to the sea and to Shihor-libnath. The explicit boundary 'to the sea' (<em>hayyāmmāh</em>) fulfills the coastal character of Asher's territory. Mount Carmel (H3760) is the great promontory jutting into the Mediterranean — the border point between Asher and Manasseh. Elijah's contest with Baal's prophets will occur here (1 Kgs 18).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The boundary turns eastward to Beth-dagon, touches Zebulun and the Valley of Iphtah-el, northward to Beth-emek and Neiel, then continues to Cabul. <em>Bêt-dāgôn</em> (H1016, house of Dagon) — a place dedicated to the Philistine grain/fish deity. The city's pagan name is recorded without comment; Asher inherits the city as real estate, its prior cultic associations now subsumed under covenant ownership.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ebron, Rehob, Hammon, Kanah — as far as Great Sidon. The northern boundary reaching to Sidon (<em>ṣîḏōn</em> H6721) fulfills the prophetic scope of Asher's territory (Gen 49:13 gives the seacoast to Zebulun, but Asher's northern reach toward Sidon is clearly anticipated). The tribe settles on the boundary of Phoenician civilization — a strategic and culturally complex position.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The boundary turns to Ramah and the fortified city of Tyre (<em>ṣōr</em> H6865), then turns toward Hosah and ends at the sea. Tyre (the Rock) is the great Phoenician maritime city — its inclusion as a boundary marker signals that Asher's northern limit was never effectively occupied. The gap between allotment and actual control characterizes these northern territories throughout the period of the Judges.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Ummah, Aphek, Rehob — twenty-two cities. Aphek (H663, fortress) appears multiple times in biblical narrative — the site of Philistine encampment before the ark's capture (1 Sam 4:1) and of other strategic engagements. The catalog of Asher's cities records both what was granted and what was never fully possessed.</p>",
    "31": "<p>This is the inheritance of Asher — closing formula. Asher's coastal territory and trade connections made it potentially the wealthiest tribe; its proximity to Phoenicia brought cultural pressure as well as commercial opportunity. The failure to drive out the Sidonians (Judg 1:31) will become a chronic spiritual vulnerability.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The sixth lot comes out for Naphtali. Gen 49:21: 'Naphtali is a doe set free that bears beautiful fawns' — a portrait of agility and eloquence. Naphtali's territory in the Upper Galilee and around the Sea of Chinnereth (Galilee) is mountainous and fertile, suited to a free-ranging tribe.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Naphtali's boundary from Heleph, the oak in Zaanannim, Adami-nekeb, and Jabneel to Lakkum, ending at the Jordan. The oak in Zaanannim (<em>ʾēlôn bəṣaʿanannîm</em> H436 H6815) will later appear as a landmark in Judges 4:11 where Heber the Kenite pitches his tent — the specific tree mentioned in the allotment list is the same tree under which the later narrative unfolds.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The boundary turns westward to Aznoth-tabor, continuing to Hukkok, touching Zebulun on the south and Asher on the west, and Judah at the Jordan on the east. The phrase 'Judah at the Jordan' is geographically puzzling since Judah does not reach the Jordan in the north — possibly referring to a Danite enclave or a textual variant. The three-directional tribal contact (Zebulun, Asher, Judah) describes Naphtali's landlocked position in the north.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The fortified cities of Naphtali: Ziddim, Zer, Hammath, Rakkath, Chinnereth — Chinnereth (H3672) gives its name to the Sea of Chinnereth (= Sea of Galilee). The city sits on the northwestern shore of the lake. Hammath (H2575, hot springs) preserves the memory of natural thermal springs at the site of later Tiberias.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Adamah, Ramah, Hazor — Hazor (H2674) is the great city-state conquered in Joshua 11, whose king Jabin is a recurring antagonist. Its inclusion in Naphtali's territory is significant: the tribe inherits the most powerful Canaanite capital, yet Judges 4 shows a Jabin of Hazor still oppressing Israel — the allotment records what was granted; the narrative records the ongoing struggle to hold it.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Kedesh, Edrei, En-hazor — Kedesh (H6943, sanctuary/holy place) in Naphtali will become one of the six cities of refuge designated in Joshua 20. The name (<em>qōḏeš</em>, holy, H6944) encodes its function as a sacred asylum site. Its designation as a refuge city is consistent with its ancient character as a sanctuary place.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Iron, Migdal-el, Horem, Beth-anath, Beth-shemesh — nineteen cities. Beth-anath (H1043, house of Anath) and Beth-shemesh (H1053, house of the sun) carry the names of Canaanite deities — Anath (warrior goddess) and Shemesh (sun god). Naphtali inherits cities named for the gods its neighbors worshiped, which may explain the spiritual pressure Naphtali faces throughout Judges.</p>",
    "39": "<p>This is the inheritance of Naphtali — closing formula. Naphtali's upper Galilean territory, surrounding the Sea of Galilee, is the same region Isaiah identifies as the land of darkness that will see a great light (Isa 9:1-2), fulfilled in Jesus's Galilean ministry (Matt 4:12-16). The allotment of Naphtali plants the geographic seed of the gospel's opening movement.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The seventh lot comes out for Dan. Dan is the last tribe to receive its allotment through the lot; its position last in the sequence may reflect its later migration story (see v47). Gen 49:16-17: 'Dan will judge his people as one of the tribes of Israel. Dan will be a serpent by the roadside' — an ambiguous portrait of cunning and independence.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Dan's territory: Zorah, Eshtaol, Ir-shemesh (city of the sun, another sun-deity name). Zorah and Eshtaol will be the hometown of Samson (Judg 13:2,25) — the great Danite judge. The allotment list situates the Samson narrative in its precise geographic home.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Shaalabbin, Aijalon (<em>ʾAyyālôn</em> H357, deer or gazelle place), Ithlah — Aijalon is the valley where Joshua commanded the sun and moon to stand still (Josh 10:12-13). The city of Aijalon (<em>ʿêmeq-ʾayyālôn</em>) gives its name to that event. It now falls in Dan's allotment, embedding the memory of the miraculous battle in the tribe's geographic inheritance.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Elon, Timnah, Ekron — Timnah (H8553) will be where Samson finds his Philistine wife (Judg 14:1), and where his father-in-law later gives her to another man (Judg 14:20). Ekron (H6138) is one of the five Philistine cities — listed in Dan's allotment though never captured. The gap between allotment and possession is starkest for Dan.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Eltekeh, Gibbethon, Baalath — Gibbethon (H1405) appears later as a Philistine city (1 Kgs 15:27; 16:15-17). Baalath (H1191, lady/Baal-place) indicates a pre-Israelite Baalistic cult site; Dan inherits territory saturated with Canaanite religious sites, which helps explain the tribe's eventual adoption of idolatrous worship (Judg 18:30-31).</p>",
    "45": "<p>Jehud, Bene-berak, Gath-rimmon — Bene-berak (H1139, sons of lightning) is later a city in the territory of Benjamin/Dan whose inhabitants were known to the Assyrian king Sennacherib (noted in his annals). The inheritance of cities later mentioned in extrabiblical documents confirms the geographic reality behind the allotment lists.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Me-jarkon and Rakkon, with the border opposite Joppa (<em>yāpôʾ</em> H3305). Joppa (modern Jaffa) is the main Mediterranean port of the central coast — the gateway through which Jonah will flee (Jon 1:3) and from which cedar for Solomon's temple will be transported (2 Chr 2:16). Dan's territory touches the coast at this strategic port, though the tribe never effectively controlled it.</p>",
    "47": "<p><em>wayyēṣēʾ gəḇûl-bənê-ḏān mēhem wayyaʿălû bənê-ḏān wayilaḥămû ʿim-lešem</em> — 'when the territory of Dan slipped from their grasp, the Danites went up and fought against Leshem.' The verb <em>yāṣāʾ mēhem</em> (H3318 + H4480 prep.) means the border 'went out from them' — the territory they were allotted proved impossible to hold. The Philistines' military pressure in the coastal plain made Dan's original inheritance untenable. This verse is the honest acknowledgment that the ideal allotment did not match the realized possession. <em>lešem</em> = Laish (cf. Judg 18:27) — Dan's migration to the far north is recorded here in compressed form; Judges 18 expands the story in detail.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The Danites captured Leshem, put it to the sword, took possession, and called it Dan after their ancestor. <em>wayyiqrəʾû ʾōtāh dān</em> — the city is renamed for the tribe. The renaming of captured territory is a covenant act: the tribe claims the city as its own by inscribing its name on it. The migration means Dan's actual possession ends up far north of its original allotment, near the headwaters of the Jordan.</p>",
    "49": "<p><em>wayəkallû liḥlōq ʾet-hāʾāreṣ ligbûlōtêhā</em> — 'when they had finished distributing the land according to its borders.' The verb <em>kālāh</em> (H3615, to complete, finish) marks the conclusion of the distribution process. <em>ligbûlōtêhā</em> (according to its borders) confirms the boundary-based system. The Israelites then give Joshua his inheritance — the commander who oversaw everyone else's distribution receives his last.</p>",
    "50": "<p>At the LORD's command (<em>ʿal-pî YHWH</em>) they give Joshua Timnath-serah in the hill country of Ephraim, which he requested. <em>ʾašer šāʾal</em> — 'which he asked/requested.' Joshua requests his own city; it is not assigned to him through the lot. <em>ʿal-pî YHWH</em> (by the mouth of YHWH) means the grant was divinely authorized. <em>wayyiḇneh ʾet-hāʿîr</em> — 'he built the city' — a founding act; Joshua does not merely inherit an existing city but establishes one, consistent with the portrait of a leader who creates rather than merely occupies.</p>",
    "51": "<p><em>ʾēlleh hannəḥālōt ʾašer niḥălû ʾelʿāzār hakkōhēn wîhôšuaʿ bin-nûn wərāʾšê hāʾāḇôt lamaṭṭôt bənê-yiśrāʾēl bəgôrāl bəšilōh lipnê YHWH</em> — the comprehensive closing formula names the three authorities: Eleazar the priest, Joshua son of Nun, and the heads of the ancestral tribes. <em>bəgôrāl</em> (by lot) and <em>lipnê YHWH</em> (before YHWH) confirm both the mechanism and the theological locus. <em>waytikallênāh ḥalleqet hāʾāreṣ</em> — 'and the apportioning of the land was complete' (<em>kālāh</em> again: finished). The distribution is closed.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH commands Joshua to establish the cities of refuge. The command had been previewed three times in the Torah: Exod 21:13 (the principle), Num 35:9-34 (the detailed law), Deut 19:1-13 (the Mosaic exposition). Joshua 20 is the implementation — the covenant instruction given at Sinai finally applied to the land. The three-stage announcement (law → exposition → application) mirrors how Israel received all major covenant institutions.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>ṯēn lākem ʾet-ʿārê hammiqlāṭ ʾăšer-dibbartî ʾălêkem bəyaḏ-mōšeh</em> — 'designate the cities of refuge of which I spoke to you by the hand of Moses.' The phrase <em>bəyaḏ-mōšeh</em> (by the hand of Moses) authorizes the command by tracing its pedigree: this is not Joshua's innovation but Moses's mandate finally enacted. <em>ʿārê hammiqlāṭ</em> (H5892 H4733) — 'cities of shelter/asylum'; <em>miqlaṭ</em> (H4733) derives from the root meaning to receive or gather in (<em>qālaṭ</em>).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The purpose: <em>lānûs šāmmāh rōṣēaḥ makkēh-nepeš bišgāgāh bəlîdāʿat</em> — 'so that a killer who strikes a person accidentally without knowledge may flee there.' Two qualifiers define the eligible manslayer: <em>bišgāgāh</em> (H7684, by mistake/inadvertently — from <em>šāgag</em>, to err, go astray) and <em>bəlî-dāʿat</em> (without knowledge/intent — H1097 H1847). The legal distinction between accident and intent (<em>šəgāgāh</em> vs. <em>zaḏôn</em>) underlies the entire Torah's graduated penalty system. The city of refuge is explicitly not available to the willful murderer (cf. Num 35:16-21). The <em>gōʾēl haddām</em> (H1350 H1818, blood-avenger/kinsman-redeemer of blood) is the kin responsible for avenging unlawful death.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>wəʿāmaḏ petaḥ šaʿar hāʿîr wəḏibber bəʾoznê ziqnê hāʿîr hahiʾ ʾet-dəḇārāyw wəʾāsəpû ʾōtô</em> — 'he shall stand at the entrance to the gate of the city and state his case to the elders.' The city gate (<em>šaʿar</em> H8179) is the locus of public judicial proceedings in ancient Israel — where contracts, legal matters, and disputes were conducted before witnesses. The manslayer must present his case (<em>dəḇārāyw</em>, his words) to the <em>zəqēnîm</em> (H2205, elders) — the civic authority. The verb <em>ʾāsap</em> (H622, to gather in, receive) is the same root as <em>miqlaṭ</em>'s related meaning: the elders 'gather him in' to the city's protection.</p>",
    "5": "<p>If the blood-avenger pursues the manslayer, the elders shall not hand him over — because 'he struck his neighbor unintentionally and was not hating him before.' The Hebrew causal chain: <em>bişgāgāh</em> (inadvertently) + <em>wəlōʾ-śōnēʾ hûʾ lô mitmōl šilšôm</em> (he was not an enemy of him previously) — the absence of prior enmity is the evidentiary test for accidental killing vs. murder. The elders function as a court of preliminary adjudication before the full assembly trial.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>wəyāšaḇ bāʿîr hahîʾ ʿaḏ-ʿomḏô lipnê hāʿēḏāh lammišpāṭ ʿaḏ-môt hakkōhēn haggāḏôl ʾašer yihyeh bayyāmîm hāhēm</em> — 'he shall live in that city until he stands before the assembly for judgment, until the death of the high priest who is serving in those days.' Three temporal markers: (1) until standing before the <em>ʿēḏāh</em> (H5712, assembly) for trial; (2) until the death of the <em>kōhēn haggāḏôl</em> (high priest); (3) after the priest's death, free to return home. The death of the high priest functions as a general amnesty — the legal logic is debated, but the pattern is clear: death of the covenant mediator releases the community from certain legal claims.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The three western cities of refuge are designated: <em>Qeḏeš</em> (H6943, sanctuary/holy place) in Galilee in the hill country of Naphtali; <em>Šekem</em> (H7927, shoulder/ridge) in the hill country of Ephraim; <em>Qiryat Arbaʿ</em> (H7153, city of four, = Hebron) in the hill country of Judah. The three cities span the north-south length of western Canaan — geography ensures that no potential manslayer is more than a half-day's journey from a city of refuge.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The three eastern cities (Transjordan) are designated: <em>Beṣer</em> (H1221, fortress/stronghold) in the wilderness plateau for Reuben; <em>Rāmôt</em> (H7216, heights) in Gilead for Gad; <em>Gôlān</em> (H1474, circuit/captive) in Bashan for Manasseh. The six cities form a network — three west, three east — ensuring symmetrical access for all twelve tribes. The Transjordan's three cities serve the two-and-a-half tribes who settled east of the Jordan in Numbers 32.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>ʾēlleh hāyû ʿārê hammuʿāḏāh</em> — 'these were the appointed cities' (<em>môʿāḏ</em> H4150, appointed meeting-place — the same word as in <em>ʾōhel môʿēd</em>, tent of meeting). The six cities of refuge are 'meeting places' of mercy and justice. The closing phrase: <em>wəlōʾ-yāmût bəyaḏ gōʾēl haddām ʿaḏ-ʿomḏô lipnê hāʿēḏāh</em> — 'so that he would not die by the hand of the blood-avenger until he had stood before the assembly.' The institution functions as due process — not exoneration, but the guarantee of a fair hearing before execution. The phrase <em>gēr</em> (H1616, sojourner/foreigner) in the last clause confirms the cities' universal scope: even the non-Israelite resident may access the asylum.</p>"
  }
}

